 
<p>
Neelie Kroes, formerly head EU official in charge of internet policy,
is accused of lobbying for Uber 
<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/2022/jul/12/eu-urged-investigate-ex-politician-uber-links-rein-in-tech-lobbyists">shortly after leaving that job.</a>
<p>
Several UK ministers met secretly 
<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/news/2022/jul/11/osborne-hancock-tory-ministers-did-not-declare-secret-uber-meetings-leak-reveals">with Uber lobbyists.</a>
<p>
Having those meetings may not violate any specific rules, but
morally speaking it suggests they are working for the wrong side.

 